  <entry>
    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2311.03348v2</id>
    <title>Scalable and Transferable Black-Box Jailbreaks for Language Models via Persona Modulation</title>
    <updated>2023-11-24T12:50:31Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.03348v2" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2311.03348v2" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>Despite efforts to align large language models to produce harmless responses, they are still vulnerable to jailbreak prompts that elicit unrestricted behaviour. In this work, we investigate persona modulation as a black-box jailbreaking method to steer a target model to take on personalities that are willing to comply with harmful instructions. Rather than manually crafting prompts for each persona, we automate the generation of jailbreaks using a language model assistant. We demonstrate a range of harmful completions made possible by persona modulation, including detailed instructions for synthesising methamphetamine, building a bomb, and laundering money. These automated attacks achieve a harmful completion rate of 42.5% in GPT-4, which is 185 times larger than before modulation (0.23%). These prompts also transfer to Claude 2 and Vicuna with harmful completion rates of 61.0% and 35.9%, respectively. Our work reveals yet another vulnerability in commercial large language models and highlights the need for more comprehensive safeguards.</summary>
